comments.body: closes #311
If you want CI to run you'll need to rebase on main - Jane and I added CircleCI and a couple basic tests when we upgraded to Ruby 3.
@faithc Just confirming--all C1703 containers currently in ASpace should be included in this request, and none of them have item records in Alma?

Ok, thanks! So since we are waiting for containers to come back from P&C, and they may potentially change, can it wait until all the containers are ready so I don't have to do this twice in short order?

I'm also noticing that the record is set to unpublished in ASpace--just so you're aware, that information doesn't come out with the export, so you may want to manually suppress the record in Alma once we've imported it.

The turnaround time for the boxes that are being treated may be somewhat significant and we were hoping to publish the finding aid and make the collection, with the exception of these few boxes, available around the end of the month. The other consideration is that it's going to likely take a couple of weeks to send the containers to ReCAP, hence the request to create the item records around the middle of the month. But if it's problematic to do this work in two batches I can check in with Alexis about waiting to publish the finding aid, though I'm not sure how long we'll be able to delay.

Also, thanks for the FYI about the need to suppress the Alma record once the item records have been added.

The finding aid needs to be published this month and should not wait for the completion of conservation treatment, which could be months.  I know it's not ideal, but, in this situation, it's really our only choice.  The other option I see is to describe the boxes in P&C now and just close them for treatment until they are available, but still they will need to be sent to ReCAP later.

aspace_helpers.title: investigate scrambled subdivisions during export from ASpace

comments.body:
As a first observation, all of these headings are coming from Resource records, i.e. are being exported via the MARC-XML endpoint of the ASpace API.

All four examples are strings in ASpace; the subdivisions are not structured as fields but merely delimited by "--". They probably date from EAD2002 (which doesn't have subdivision attributes) several migrations ago (possibly by ways of Archivists' Toolkit).

The relevant code starts at https://github.com/pulibrary/aspace_helpers/blob/main/reports/aspace2alma/get_MARCxml.rb#L115
It tokenizes the string on "--", then checks each segment for numerals.
I suspect the bug is `new_subfield_a[0].next` in L126.
Fixed and deployed.

figgy.title: Enable optimistic locking for all resources
Resources should create a Tombstone when they're deleted

comments.body:
These are the things we tried, some of which may be useful for a migration as part of the above:

CTE + ROW_NUMBER (could be adjusted to find everything that's not the first row)
```sql
WITH summary AS (
  SELECT res.*, ROW_NUMBER() OVER(PARTITION BY res.metadata->>'child_id' ORDER BY res.updated_at DESC) AS rank 
  FROM orm_resources res 
  WHERE res.internal_resource = 'Event'
) 
SELECT * from summary
WHERE rank = 1 AND metadata @> '{"status": ["FAILURE"]}'
ORDER BY updated_at ASC LIMIT 50;
```

SELECT DISTINCT
```sql
WITH summary AS (
  SELECT DISTINCT ON (metadata->>'child_id') * FROM orm_resources WHERE internal_resource = 'Event' ORDER BY metadata->>'child_id', updated_at DESC LIMIT 50
) select * from summary WHERE metadata @> '{"status": ["FAILURE"]}' ORDER BY updated_at ASC LIMIT 50;
```


Indexes we built to speed up SELECT DISTINCT and CTE/ROW_NUMBER

```sql
CREATE INDEX event_metadata_child_id_idx ON orm_resources ((metadata->>'child_id'), updated_at DESC) WHERE (internal_resource) = 'Event'
```

Existing query, but minus a few checks (resource_id and child_property):
```sql
SELECT res.* FROM orm_resources AS res WHERE NOT EXISTS (
  SELECT a.* FROM orm_resources AS a WHERE
  a.internal_resource = res.internal_resource AND
  a.metadata @> '{"status": ["SUCCESS"]}' AND
  a.metadata->'child_id' = res.metadata->'child_id' AND
  a.updated_at >= res.updated_at
) AND
res.metadata @> '{"status": ["FAILURE"]}' AND
res.internal_resource = 'Event'
ORDER BY res.updated_at ASC
LIMIT 50
```

Removing those extra checks cut off like a second, not significant enough to do.

pdc_describe.title: Simplify logic: use `find_by_value` instead of `elsif` chain
Factored out the list of works, which makes the work model smaller.
Loop over title types in ERB
Ensuring that Work#approve logs a message indicating that the Work was successfully published by the curator user
Rename the variable from hash to jsonb_hash
Make relation type validation consistent with the values provided

comments.body: I think this is ready to go... but it is a lot of changes. In the middle of the effort, it seemed like it would be simpler to try to handle all the cases the same way, but in the end it involved more tweaks than I had anticipated. This does not include a migration: Instead, it just makes sure we can read both new (datacite value) and old (datacite key/upcased value) JSON. Writing a migration task could be a follow-up, unless reviewers think it should also be added to this PR.

pulfalight.title: Some documents can't be exported to XML

comments.body:
In the most recent case:
 https://findingaids.princeton.edu/catalog/AC198-05_c1791.xml

The document contains "id="AC198.05_c1791" while the id of the page is "id="AC198_05_c1791", so the this line raises an error:
https://github.com/pulibrary/pulfalight/blob/815f2f13e092cd034c7d31311ae50aabe47c02d9/app/models/pulfalight/document/xml_export.rb#L14

The solution is to make the the xpath query more flexible.
related: https://github.com/pulibrary/pulfalight/issues/1185
